      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, my realtor just mentioned i need to set up an escrow account for this house i'm buying in toronto. what actually is escrow and why can't i just pay the seller directly?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Escrow in Toronto, you say? Well, it's a bit like a trusty little sidekick, just like a loyal house-elf, keeping an eye on things until the big reveal. In this case, the escrow account is a separate bank account that holds funds until certain conditions are met, like the sale being finalized and the property being transferred to your name. It's a way to ensure that the funds are released only when everything is in order, preventing any potential disputes or misunderstandings.\n\nThink of it like a tiny, digital goblin guarding the treasure chest of your down payment. If everything checks out, the goblin releases the funds, and you get to claim your new home. But if there are any issues, the goblin holds onto the money until they're resolved, keeping everything fair and square.\n\nAs for paying the seller directly, it's not a bad idea, but it's not always the best option. You see, in Ontario, the law requires that the seller receive payment through a licensed real estate agent or a lawyer, who then holds the funds in an escrow account until the sale is complete. This helps prevent any potential disputes or issues with the sale, and it also ensures that the funds are",
