    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "wait, a goblin? lol why would you say that? anyway, you mentioned a lawyer or agent holds it. what exactly happens if there's a problem with the house inspection right before closing? does the escrow thing protect my money then?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "No goblin, I swear! I just like to think of escrow as a little bit like a goblin's treasure hoard - it's a safe place to stash your money until everything is just right.\n\nNow, about those problems with the house inspection... If there's a major issue with the property, like structural damage or a hidden defect, it can be a real challenge to resolve before closing. That's where the escrow account comes in handy. If the inspection reveals a significant problem, the seller might need to fix it or negotiate a price reduction. In either case, the escrow account holds the funds until the issue is resolved.\n\nThink of it like a goblin's contract - if the seller doesn't meet their end of the bargain, the goblin (escrow) gets to keep the money until everything is square. This way, you can be sure that your down payment is safe and secure, and you won't be stuck with a problematic property.\n\nIn some cases, the escrow account might even require the seller to provide a repair estimate or a plan for fixing the issue before the funds are released. It's a way to ensure that both parties are on the same page and that the sale is completed smoothly.",
